WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:03.690
Hello, and welcome to the educational session on epistasis and

2
00:00:03.740 --> 00:00:07.620
evolution, how genetic interactions shape cancer trajectories.

3
00:00:07.760 --> 00:00:10.000
I'm really pleased to see everyone here today.

4
00:00:10.820 --> 00:00:13.660
We have a good lineup of speakers to talk about the topic.

5
00:00:14.620 --> 00:00:17.500
I just want to remind everyone about the way that this is scheduled.

6
00:00:17.540 --> 00:00:21.360
We're going to each have 20 minutes to talk for the

7
00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:23.700
speakers with five minutes for questions afterwards.

8
00:00:23.720 --> 00:00:27.570
So please do ask your questions in the five minutes, but if you're thinking about a

9
00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:31.500
complex question or a simple question, maybe the simple questions during the

10
00:00:31.580 --> 00:00:34.780
five minutes afterward, because we're going to have a panel discussion at the end.

11
00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:38.660
So if it's a broader, more theoretical, longer question, you may want to

12
00:00:38.680 --> 00:00:42.460
reserve that for the panel discussion at the end of the session, okay?

13
00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:44.500
Thanks very much again for your attention here.

14
00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:47.530
I'm just going to move right along then

15
00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:50.080
to our first speaker,

16
00:00:51.140 --> 00:00:51.880
Jaime Aranzo,

17
00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:56.120
who has done some excellent work on epistasis and evolution and will be

18
00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:58.740
explaining some of that to you today.

19
00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:00.879
Come on up, Jaime.

20
00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:02.360
Welcome him, please.

21
00:01:14.840 --> 00:01:18.520
All right. So good morning, and thank you for the

22
00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:20.960
introduction and for putting together this session.

23
00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:26.340
Today, I'm going to talk about genetic interactions in cancer, how to detect

24
00:01:26.380 --> 00:01:28.480
them, how to model them, and why we should care.

25
00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:34.320
As you probably know, cancer is an evolutionary process that happens

26
00:01:34.380 --> 00:01:38.000
within our bodies and during our lifetime.

27
00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:39.880
The process starts when a cell

28
00:01:40.860 --> 00:01:44.460
acquires a mutation that provides it a fitness advantage

29
00:01:44.540 --> 00:01:48.360
over the adjacent cells. So the cell is going to

30
00:01:48.380 --> 00:01:51.860
proliferate, it's going to become locally abundant, and it's going to establish a

31
00:01:51.880 --> 00:01:53.380
population of cells with a mutation.

32
00:01:54.320 --> 00:01:57.980
Okay, the population can accumulate further mutations, and sometimes in the end,

33
00:01:58.020 --> 00:02:00.640
that eventually may end up leading to cancer.

34
00:02:02.180 --> 00:02:05.900
These mutations that promote cancer progression are called drivers,

35
00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:10.000
and they tend to occur in specific genes that we call cancer genes.

36
00:02:11.300 --> 00:02:12.000
An important

37
00:02:12.860 --> 00:02:16.080
detail is that driver mutations are a minority.

38
00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:19.900
So most of the mutations are neutral or even slightly

39
00:02:19.940 --> 00:02:22.600
deleterious from the perspective of tumor progression.

40
00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:24.900
We call those passengers.

41
00:02:27.180 --> 00:02:29.080
So I probably don't need to convince you that

42
00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:32.840
identifying and quantifying drivers is relevant.

43
00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:37.000
They're going to give us information about the genetic basis for cancer,

44
00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:41.540
and they can also help us identify potential therapeutical targets.

45
00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:44.080
But it is a challenging task,

46
00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:46.660
mostly because they are the minority.

47
00:02:48.540 --> 00:02:50.560
So how can we infer driver mutations?

48
00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:53.520
There are several approaches to that.

49
00:02:53.560 --> 00:02:56.440
The one I'm going to present is, I like it especially because it

50
00:02:56.500 --> 00:02:59.829
uses methods and ideas from evolutionary genetics.

51
00:03:00.700 --> 00:03:04.420
So the idea is that we start from a very large collection of cancer sequencing data

52
00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:07.680
for the cancer type of interest.

53
00:03:09.040 --> 00:03:12.860
From that collection, we are going to extract synonymous mutations, and we are

54
00:03:12.900 --> 00:03:15.000
going to use those mutations to

55
00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:19.140
build a mathematical model, a null model of

56
00:03:19.460 --> 00:03:23.000
mutations. So with that model, with that statistical model, we

57
00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:26.780
can estimate the expected number of

58
00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:30.390
mutations that we will see in a tumor in the absence of

59
00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:33.180
selection. And that's why we're using synonymous mutations.

60
00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:36.740
We assume that they are silent, and because of that, they are not subject to

61
00:03:36.780 --> 00:03:37.200
selection.

62
00:03:38.460 --> 00:03:42.380
Now, we can also estimate the number of non-synonymous mutations that we would

63
00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:44.520
expect in the absence of selection.

64
00:03:45.060 --> 00:03:46.920
And then what we do is to compare that number

65
00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:51.980
with the observed number of non-synonymous substitutions or mutations in

66
00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:52.380
general.

67
00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:55.000
And then we calculate the difference,

68
00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:59.720
and the difference is equal to the number of mutations that have reached detectable

69
00:03:59.760 --> 00:04:01.980
frequencies in our sample because of selection.

70
00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:04.460
And within our evolutionary framework,

71
00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:08.800
mutations subject to positive selection are the driver mutations.

72
00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:09.340
So we

73
00:04:11.180 --> 00:04:13.940
can not only say if there are driver mutations in a gene or not, we can actually

74
00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:17.120
quantify how many or how often we find them per sample.

75
00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:21.760
This is implemented in a software called the NDSCV that was developed by Iñigo

76
00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:24.420
Martín-Correa from Sanger Institute. So this is not our work.

77
00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:28.200
But

78
00:04:29.560 --> 00:04:32.180
also, you probably know driver mutations do not act alone.

79
00:04:32.540 --> 00:04:36.220
Okay, so we have the drivers, but we know that often we need more than one

80
00:04:36.260 --> 00:04:40.040
driver to induce cancer, and actually, very often, drivers work

81
00:04:40.080 --> 00:04:42.480
together. This is a classical example, MYC and K-RAS.

82
00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:45.580
So if both of them are together, they can promote tumors.

83
00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:47.780
If we only have one, normally nothing happens.

84
00:04:48.440 --> 00:04:52.420
And that's a classical example of genetic epistasis in cancer.

85
00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:55.140
So the idea of epistasis is that the effect of

86
00:04:55.940 --> 00:04:59.740
a mutation depends on what other mutations are present in a

87
00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:00.060
cell.

88
00:05:01.380 --> 00:05:05.120
We can formalize this mathematically. I'm going to show it more graphically.

89
00:05:05.960 --> 00:05:09.420
So this will be the idea. Imagine that we have two genes, gene A and gene B, both

90
00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:13.400
are cancer genes. And then we look at what's the tumorigenic potential

91
00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:16.600
of mutations in gene A, this one here. Can you see there?

92
00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:21.040
Yeah. So if there are only genes in this particular example, if there are mutations

93
00:05:21.050 --> 00:05:24.520
in gene A, nothing happens. The tumorigenic potential doesn't increase.

94
00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:28.560
But if we have mutations in A and B, then the cell becomes very tumorigenic.

95
00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:32.440
So the effect of this mutation in A depends on whether we have mutations in B or

96
00:05:32.500 --> 00:05:32.700
not.

97
00:05:33.860 --> 00:05:37.700
We call this positive epistasis, and in terms of selection, what we

98
00:05:37.740 --> 00:05:41.660
would find is that selection for mutations in A only happens if

99
00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:44.960
there are also selections in B. We have conditional selection.

100
00:05:46.220 --> 00:05:49.740
The same for negative epistasis. In this case, mutations in A are tumorigenic,

101
00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:51.440
but if there are also mutations in B,

102
00:05:52.370 --> 00:05:53.520
it doesn't work so well for the cell.

103
00:05:54.280 --> 00:05:57.380
That's negative epistasis, and in terms of selection, we will see that

104
00:05:57.920 --> 00:06:01.640
selection for drivers in gene A is conditional to having also

105
00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:05.516
drivers in gene BAnd just as a note,

106
00:06:05.936 --> 00:06:07.936
synthetic lethality will be an extreme case of this.

107
00:06:07.996 --> 00:06:10.236
It's when we have double mutation, it's lethal for the tumor.

108
00:06:12.116 --> 00:06:13.316
So now we have this

109
00:06:14.196 --> 00:06:18.106
mathematical theory of how epistasis relates to conditional selection, we can

110
00:06:18.156 --> 00:06:22.116
actually design an algorithm to quantify epistasis.

111
00:06:22.776 --> 00:06:26.516
It is the following. We start again with a large data set of

112
00:06:26.556 --> 00:06:30.396
cancer sequences. We are using The Cancer Genome Atlas.

113
00:06:30.456 --> 00:06:34.196
And then what we're going to do is to stratify our data set in two groups.

114
00:06:34.976 --> 00:06:38.936
One that has mutations in a given gene, we call it the split gene, will be B in the

115
00:06:39.036 --> 00:06:39.736
previous example.

116
00:06:40.576 --> 00:06:44.095
And then for each group, we are going to estimate selection,

117
00:06:45.356 --> 00:06:48.136
using the strategy that I presented before, the NDSCV.

118
00:06:49.836 --> 00:06:53.146
And we apply that to a query gene, the gene A in the previous example.

119
00:06:53.776 --> 00:06:56.056
And then we compare the number of drivers

120
00:06:56.896 --> 00:06:57.676
in both groups.

121
00:06:58.516 --> 00:07:02.076
Okay? If that difference is positive, it means that there is positive epistasis

122
00:07:02.116 --> 00:07:06.016
between mutations in genes A and B. There is synergy between those two genes.

123
00:07:07.136 --> 00:07:10.716
And if the difference is negative, it means that there is negative epistasis, so

124
00:07:10.756 --> 00:07:12.736
there is interference between those two genes.

125
00:07:13.836 --> 00:07:17.716
We put together this algorithm in an R package called cosalliance that you

126
00:07:17.756 --> 00:07:21.646
can find in GitHub. And there is also, we published a tutorial, and

127
00:07:21.696 --> 00:07:24.936
if you want to use it and have difficulties, you can feel free to contact me.

128
00:07:26.176 --> 00:07:26.336
So

129
00:07:28.376 --> 00:07:32.296
let's put this into practice, and let's see what we can learn about epistasis in

130
00:07:32.336 --> 00:07:32.696
cancer.

131
00:07:34.296 --> 00:07:38.276
One of the things what we found is that positive and negative epistasis is quite

132
00:07:38.316 --> 00:07:42.016
abundant. And actually, positive epistasis is more frequent than

133
00:07:42.036 --> 00:07:43.896
negative epistasis. We see a lot of synergy.

134
00:07:45.256 --> 00:07:48.936
Also, when we compare among different cancer types, we see that there is some

135
00:07:48.956 --> 00:07:52.916
variability, but in general, between one-quarter and one-half of

136
00:07:52.976 --> 00:07:56.396
driver mutations are affected by positive

137
00:07:56.436 --> 00:08:00.426
epistasis. So this is important, qualitatively and

138
00:08:00.496 --> 00:08:01.236
quantitatively.

139
00:08:02.636 --> 00:08:04.616
But we can go a bit farther than that.

140
00:08:05.416 --> 00:08:09.016
We can build epistasis networks. So I'm going to describe what it is.

141
00:08:09.736 --> 00:08:12.555
Here, each circle will represent a cancer gene.

142
00:08:13.436 --> 00:08:17.196
The size is proportional to how often that cancer gene has driver

143
00:08:17.216 --> 00:08:19.036
mutations in a particular cancer type,

144
00:08:20.036 --> 00:08:23.956
and the arrows show if there is positive, green, or negative, purple,

145
00:08:24.336 --> 00:08:24.996
epistasis.

146
00:08:26.696 --> 00:08:30.656
This may remind you of analysis of co-occurrence and mutual

147
00:08:30.696 --> 00:08:34.437
exclusivity in cancer, and that's because it has something to do with

148
00:08:34.516 --> 00:08:38.427
that. There is a difference. We are building these networks using

149
00:08:38.456 --> 00:08:42.236
this idea of conditional selection, and that helps us control

150
00:08:42.297 --> 00:08:46.096
for confounding variables like mutational load, difference in

151
00:08:46.116 --> 00:08:49.976
mutational profiles, and we can also identify asymmetric relationships.

152
00:08:50.816 --> 00:08:51.916
I will talk about that later.

153
00:08:53.076 --> 00:08:56.196
Also, something that I want to point out in this figure, this is quite

154
00:08:56.216 --> 00:09:00.136
representative, is that these networks typically are something that we call sign

155
00:09:00.176 --> 00:09:03.716
modular. So you can identify modules like these three genes here,

156
00:09:04.696 --> 00:09:08.536
or these four genes here, of genes that are synergistically with

157
00:09:08.556 --> 00:09:08.976
each other,

158
00:09:10.576 --> 00:09:13.756
and they are antagonistic with the genes from different modules.

159
00:09:14.536 --> 00:09:16.736
And that has interesting implications.

160
00:09:17.836 --> 00:09:19.056
So this is as a cartoon.

161
00:09:19.936 --> 00:09:23.716
In a real example, this will be the network for low-grade glioma, and I

162
00:09:23.836 --> 00:09:27.376
will show you these modules that I just described. Here, we have three genes.

163
00:09:27.856 --> 00:09:30.116
They are all connected by positive interactions.

164
00:09:31.576 --> 00:09:35.316
Then we have two genes here, will be a second module, third module

165
00:09:35.376 --> 00:09:38.476
here, and then four and five are two isolated genes.

166
00:09:39.476 --> 00:09:42.616
The idea of this modular structure is that,

167
00:09:43.736 --> 00:09:47.656
once you have mutations in a given module, selection is going to promote

168
00:09:48.836 --> 00:09:51.596
other mutations in the same module, and it's going to go against mutations in

169
00:09:51.616 --> 00:09:55.156
different modules. So if you look at a particular tumor in a particular patient,

170
00:09:55.496 --> 00:09:58.956
you will typically find mutations only in one of these modules of the network.

171
00:09:59.896 --> 00:10:03.716
And because of that, we can classify a tumor based on which genes of the

172
00:10:03.736 --> 00:10:06.976
epistasis network are being active or have mutated.

173
00:10:08.076 --> 00:10:10.776
Once we have that, we can, for example, compare the survival.

174
00:10:11.556 --> 00:10:15.486
This is the data for this particular tumor, and we see that different modules of

175
00:10:15.516 --> 00:10:18.736
the epistasis network are associated with significantly different survival.

176
00:10:19.516 --> 00:10:23.236
So this is helpful because it tells us that it's not just individual genes.

177
00:10:23.456 --> 00:10:27.436
We can use sets of genes to make better predictions about patient survival.

178
00:10:28.356 --> 00:10:31.936
First message to take home, mutational profiles associated with network

179
00:10:31.996 --> 00:10:34.156
modules are informative of patient survival.

180
00:10:37.716 --> 00:10:41.616
We can go a step further. We can look at other tumors, and we can identify

181
00:10:41.636 --> 00:10:43.556
these modules and see what else can we learn.

182
00:10:44.176 --> 00:10:44.536
So here,

183
00:10:45.376 --> 00:10:49.356
I want to point out something that came out to-- we realized when we were

184
00:10:49.376 --> 00:10:53.096
looking at these networks, is that the modules of the network typically have a

185
00:10:53.116 --> 00:10:56.976
correspondence with genes that are associated with specific

186
00:10:57.276 --> 00:11:00.596
molecular subtypes or well-characterized clinical subtypes of tumor.

187
00:11:01.096 --> 00:11:04.376
For example, for endometrial cancer on the left, we have this module here.

188
00:11:04.796 --> 00:11:07.676
If we look at the genes in that module, those are the genes that are typically

189
00:11:07.756 --> 00:11:11.216
mutated in endometrioid type 1 endometrial cancers.

190
00:11:12.576 --> 00:11:16.116
These other two genes are the typical markers of copy number high

191
00:11:16.396 --> 00:11:19.776
subtype. And for colorectal cancer, we have the same.

192
00:11:19.816 --> 00:11:23.736
This will be the module associated with a canonical pathway to colorectal cancer.

193
00:11:24.746 --> 00:11:26.116
This other module is associated with

194
00:11:27.376 --> 00:11:28.956
consensus molecular subtype 1.

195
00:11:30.456 --> 00:11:34.256
So there seems to be this association, and now when we try to zoom out

196
00:11:34.436 --> 00:11:38.216
and go into some more conceptual question, is if you think of tumors

197
00:11:38.396 --> 00:11:42.036
in different patients and you think of them as evolutionary processes,

198
00:11:42.636 --> 00:11:44.516
they are completely independent processes.

199
00:11:44.696 --> 00:11:48.116
So a tumor in a person and a different person, those have happened

200
00:11:48.336 --> 00:11:51.636
independently. Mutations have been accumulated independently.

201
00:11:51.656 --> 00:11:54.036
Those are completely independent evolutionary

202
00:11:55.856 --> 00:11:59.436
trajectories. However, the fact that we can

203
00:11:59.476 --> 00:12:02.936
define clinical and molecular subtypes means that they actually

204
00:12:02.976 --> 00:12:06.576
converge towards some specific phenotypes.So for an

205
00:12:06.616 --> 00:12:07.776
evolutionary biologist like me,

206
00:12:09.176 --> 00:12:12.496
that's quite interesting because that's an example of evolutionary

207
00:12:12.516 --> 00:12:16.166
convergence. We see independent processes leading to the same

208
00:12:16.236 --> 00:12:16.656
outcomes.

209
00:12:17.616 --> 00:12:20.376
And the formal question here is: why does it happen?

210
00:12:20.656 --> 00:12:22.956
What is driving this evolutionary convergence of cancer?

211
00:12:23.956 --> 00:12:27.016
Now, our hypothesis is that the key is this modular

212
00:12:27.536 --> 00:12:30.456
architecture of epistasis network. Okay?

213
00:12:30.496 --> 00:12:34.056
We hypothesize that when you have a modular epistasis network,

214
00:12:34.596 --> 00:12:38.016
evolutionary processes on those networks are going to be canalized towards specific

215
00:12:38.025 --> 00:12:41.536
phenotypes, which would correspond, in the case of cancer, to consensus molecular

216
00:12:41.556 --> 00:12:42.886
subtypes or clinical subtypes.

217
00:12:44.516 --> 00:12:45.836
To test that hypothesis,

218
00:12:46.756 --> 00:12:50.716
we did some mathematical models. So we started with

219
00:12:50.796 --> 00:12:54.276
the empirical epistasis networks and also with toy ones.

220
00:12:55.136 --> 00:12:58.336
We basically simulated the process by which cells accumulate mutations, then there

221
00:12:58.356 --> 00:13:02.036
is selection, and in the end, what we have for each realization of the model is a

222
00:13:02.076 --> 00:13:02.456
matrix

223
00:13:03.416 --> 00:13:06.976
with the genes in the columns and the different replicates in our

224
00:13:07.336 --> 00:13:11.096
in silico tumors in the rows, and then we know which genes are mutated in

225
00:13:11.336 --> 00:13:14.756
which tumors. Then we can run a PCA and see if there are

226
00:13:15.916 --> 00:13:17.416
classes of tumors, like different groups.

227
00:13:17.476 --> 00:13:19.076
This is basically we are trying to

228
00:13:20.136 --> 00:13:21.016
replicate this idea of

229
00:13:22.096 --> 00:13:25.716
investigating possible subtypes from our in silico data.

230
00:13:27.006 --> 00:13:30.876
And what we found is that for some structures of the network, we

231
00:13:30.916 --> 00:13:33.756
can recover different well-determined

232
00:13:34.736 --> 00:13:36.956
subtypes, and that happens when the network has these

233
00:13:37.836 --> 00:13:40.396
kind of structures here. So it's basically signed modular.

234
00:13:41.056 --> 00:13:43.556
This will be more or less what we see in real tumors.

235
00:13:45.236 --> 00:13:46.786
So I think interesting here is that

236
00:13:47.696 --> 00:13:51.536
actually in these networks, the first mutation determines which

237
00:13:51.576 --> 00:13:53.116
module of the network is going to be mutated.

238
00:13:53.456 --> 00:13:57.176
So if the first mutation falls here on the left module, for example,

239
00:13:57.996 --> 00:14:01.396
the tumor is going to evolve to this subtype, to the left subtype.

240
00:14:01.476 --> 00:14:05.316
If the first mutation falls here, just by chance, the tumor is going to

241
00:14:05.376 --> 00:14:06.916
evolve to this right subtype,

242
00:14:07.976 --> 00:14:11.536
which means that just by knowing very early

243
00:14:11.596 --> 00:14:15.396
mutations, we can predict what subtype of tumor is going to

244
00:14:15.436 --> 00:14:18.816
evolve, assuming that that lineage actually evolves into cancer.

245
00:14:20.156 --> 00:14:23.936
So that will be the second take-home message, is that early

246
00:14:23.956 --> 00:14:27.816
mutations in these pretumoral lesions can help predict

247
00:14:28.296 --> 00:14:31.925
future tumor subtypes. And that's, again, because of this

248
00:14:32.196 --> 00:14:35.976
particular structure of epistasis networks in cancer.

249
00:14:39.286 --> 00:14:40.066
And then I will

250
00:14:42.016 --> 00:14:44.856
go back to this idea of asymmetry in epistasis.

251
00:14:45.956 --> 00:14:49.836
So as I mentioned before, because we use conditional selection to

252
00:14:49.856 --> 00:14:52.836
infer epistasis, we can actually infer asymmetric relationships.

253
00:14:53.816 --> 00:14:57.656
Some of them, like this here on the top, are symmetric, so APC and TP53

254
00:14:57.736 --> 00:15:01.556
in colon cancer. In principle, both are synergistic with each other.

255
00:15:02.656 --> 00:15:03.556
So it doesn't matter

256
00:15:04.536 --> 00:15:08.016
if the mutation occurs first in APC or in TP53, the

257
00:15:08.116 --> 00:15:10.456
synergistic effect is going to work more or less the same.

258
00:15:12.236 --> 00:15:14.796
And then we have other cases, like these ones that I'm showing at the bottom,

259
00:15:16.316 --> 00:15:17.876
where the epistasis is clearly asymmetric.

260
00:15:18.516 --> 00:15:20.816
So, say, a mutation in TP53

261
00:15:21.676 --> 00:15:25.516
critically increases the effect of mutations on this RB1 gene in

262
00:15:25.536 --> 00:15:27.656
glioblastoma, but not vice versa.

263
00:15:28.096 --> 00:15:31.016
If we have first the mutation in this RB1 gene,

264
00:15:31.876 --> 00:15:33.876
then that doesn't really modify the

265
00:15:34.796 --> 00:15:36.166
tumorigenic effect of TP53,

266
00:15:37.196 --> 00:15:38.546
which is the same for many other genes.

267
00:15:39.836 --> 00:15:41.156
This asymmetry is actually

268
00:15:42.136 --> 00:15:45.956
establishing some sort of logical ordering for

269
00:15:46.016 --> 00:15:49.476
mutations. So the idea is that if we have a mutation first in this first gene,

270
00:15:49.896 --> 00:15:52.136
then mutations in these genes are going to have an effect.

271
00:15:52.556 --> 00:15:53.616
If it's in the other

272
00:15:54.636 --> 00:15:56.356
direction, doesn't really matter.

273
00:15:57.496 --> 00:15:58.136
And because of that,

274
00:15:59.696 --> 00:16:03.656
what we concluded is that asymmetry in the epistasis network is informative of

275
00:16:03.716 --> 00:16:05.056
the order in which mutations happen.

276
00:16:05.336 --> 00:16:09.096
So we tested that with genetic mutation data, which is this

277
00:16:09.106 --> 00:16:12.016
figure on the right, and we saw that this idea is true.

278
00:16:12.776 --> 00:16:16.606
So basically, the directionality of the epistasis network is informative

279
00:16:16.696 --> 00:16:19.376
of the temporal sequence in which mutations occur.

280
00:16:19.806 --> 00:16:23.656
It's basically telling us that there is a primary cancer gene and then a

281
00:16:23.716 --> 00:16:24.696
secondary cancer gene.

282
00:16:26.396 --> 00:16:29.196
That's about the directionality of the interactions.

283
00:16:29.716 --> 00:16:33.496
We can also look at the position of a gene in the epistasis network.

284
00:16:35.296 --> 00:16:37.756
So this is also a theoretical

285
00:16:39.056 --> 00:16:40.856
work that we did a couple of years ago.

286
00:16:41.936 --> 00:16:45.916
And here we study basically how does the position of

287
00:16:45.936 --> 00:16:49.096
a gene in the network affect its tumorigenic potential.

288
00:16:50.216 --> 00:16:54.076
In this particular case, we are studying a scenario in which the tumor

289
00:16:54.156 --> 00:16:56.516
can also accumulate slightly deleterious mutations.

290
00:16:57.006 --> 00:17:00.666
And because of that, basically, there is tug-of-war between driver mutations and

291
00:17:00.716 --> 00:17:04.096
passenger mutations. You need to accumulate drivers fast enough to actually escape

292
00:17:04.176 --> 00:17:06.237
this deleterious effect of passengers.

293
00:17:06.636 --> 00:17:10.216
Otherwise, the tumor doesn't progress, which is a model that has been proposed to

294
00:17:10.237 --> 00:17:14.216
explain why many healthy tissues or just

295
00:17:14.257 --> 00:17:17.206
regular tissue have driver mutations and they never progress to cancer.

296
00:17:18.487 --> 00:17:22.237
And what we found is that actually cancer happens when you have a mutation

297
00:17:22.316 --> 00:17:25.196
in key genes of the epistasis network,

298
00:17:25.977 --> 00:17:29.636
especially in genes that occupy central positions of the network.

299
00:17:30.656 --> 00:17:31.646
So this is telling us that

300
00:17:33.436 --> 00:17:36.996
the position that the gene occupies in the epistasis network is relevant, and

301
00:17:37.056 --> 00:17:41.016
actually those that are hubs, that are here in central positions,

302
00:17:41.376 --> 00:17:45.316
are acting as gatekeepers. It's not the same to get an early mutation in a

303
00:17:45.336 --> 00:17:46.996
peripheral gene than in a central gene.

304
00:17:47.696 --> 00:17:51.116
So again, by determining the structure of epistasis network, we can identify which

305
00:17:51.276 --> 00:17:53.156
genes are these potential gatekeepers.

306
00:17:53.956 --> 00:17:57.756
This is all based on simulations. We are now

307
00:17:57.816 --> 00:18:01.796
working on verifying this with actual data from cancer models

308
00:18:01.836 --> 00:18:02.276
in mouse.

309
00:18:04.036 --> 00:18:07.036
So the third message would be that the structure of epistasis network reveals

310
00:18:07.056 --> 00:18:10.996
central gatekeeper genes.And, well, I'm

311
00:18:11.156 --> 00:18:14.236
a bit quick today, so with this, I'm getting to the

312
00:18:15.216 --> 00:18:17.496
final conclusion. We'll have more time for discussion, so that's good.

313
00:18:18.576 --> 00:18:21.376
The first idea that epistasis is pervasive in cancer evolution.

314
00:18:22.006 --> 00:18:24.466
This epistasis network organizing modules,

315
00:18:25.776 --> 00:18:29.506
which are groups of genes that act in synergy to promote cancer progression

316
00:18:29.776 --> 00:18:33.036
and have widespread antagonism between genes of different

317
00:18:34.616 --> 00:18:34.996
modules.

318
00:18:36.916 --> 00:18:38.796
The epistasis networks are informative.

319
00:18:40.116 --> 00:18:43.536
They are informative of different patient survival, so we can get better

320
00:18:43.556 --> 00:18:47.536
predictions by looking at sets of genes instead of at individual genes.

321
00:18:49.816 --> 00:18:53.276
By mapping early mutations to their corresponding network modules,

322
00:18:53.816 --> 00:18:55.516
we can predict future properties for the tumor.

323
00:18:55.836 --> 00:18:59.436
Particularly, we can predict which is the future subtype that will evolve from that

324
00:18:59.836 --> 00:19:01.216
pretumoral population.

325
00:19:02.156 --> 00:19:05.236
And finally, central genes in the epistasis network act as gatekeepers,

326
00:19:05.976 --> 00:19:09.116
so determining the network can help us identify key genes.

