00:28:41.748 --> 00:28:45.568
things be going on there. Because co-occurrence

495
00:28:45.688 --> 00:28:48.988
tells you that mutations appear together, but not why they appear together.

496
00:28:49.608 --> 00:28:51.948
It could be because just mutations

497
00:28:51.988 --> 00:28:54.828
occur very often.

498
00:28:56.328 --> 00:29:00.188
And so it cannot separate the mutagenic environment from selection.

499
00:29:00.348 --> 00:29:03.988
So something that is highly mutable in a

500
00:29:04.028 --> 00:29:04.888
particular

501
00:29:06.108 --> 00:29:09.448
cancer, that will co-occur with almost everything.

502
00:29:10.968 --> 00:29:14.928
And then the other thing that already Jaime was pointing out is you don't

503
00:29:14.968 --> 00:29:18.648
have any directionality. You don't know which mutation came first,

504
00:29:19.368 --> 00:29:23.218
and if it is something where A gives you an advantage of

505
00:29:23.408 --> 00:29:27.388
getting B or the other way around. If B gives you an advantage of getting

506
00:29:27.448 --> 00:29:27.568
A.

507
00:29:29.188 --> 00:29:33.128
And the other thing about co-occurrence and mutual exclusivity is

508
00:29:33.168 --> 00:29:37.028
that it's purely pairwise. So you cannot scale that to

509
00:29:37.048 --> 00:29:38.468
consider triplets of genes.

510
00:29:40.308 --> 00:29:43.868
And besides, you cannot formally test whether different

511
00:29:43.908 --> 00:29:47.308
epistatic effects occurred in different kinds

512
00:29:47.348 --> 00:29:50.868
of populations. So I'll be

513
00:29:50.928 --> 00:29:54.788
introducing here a little bit of what Jeff is going to talk about in the

514
00:29:54.828 --> 00:29:58.698
next talk. He's going to be talking about smokers and nonsmokers,

515
00:29:58.768 --> 00:30:01.708
but just want you to keep that in mind.

516
00:30:02.748 --> 00:30:06.668
So generally, we'll start here,

517
00:30:06.728 --> 00:30:09.108
the model. I'll just show you the model in general.

518
00:30:10.148 --> 00:30:11.968
We have what is called a substitution rate.

519
00:30:12.028 --> 00:30:14.788
So you don't have a mutation, and then you observe it in tumors.

520
00:30:15.308 --> 00:30:19.228
So in order to observe it in tumors, then the mutation has to be occurring at

521
00:30:19.268 --> 00:30:22.888
a certain rate. And that rate is going to be

522
00:30:23.028 --> 00:30:26.856
combiningThe mutation rate, so

523
00:30:26.916 --> 00:30:30.756
how often things actually occur in the cell with this

524
00:30:30.796 --> 00:30:32.556
part of fixation, which is the selection.

525
00:30:33.396 --> 00:30:36.456
Okay. And whenever you introduce another gene,

526
00:30:37.196 --> 00:30:39.376
then you can check

527
00:30:40.236 --> 00:30:43.776
if these two rates at which things are occurring,

528
00:30:44.356 --> 00:30:45.816
if they are different from each other.

529
00:30:46.516 --> 00:30:49.656
So if the presence of B changes how

530
00:30:50.356 --> 00:30:54.116
often you get to AB compared to whenever you don't have

531
00:30:55.096 --> 00:30:55.196
B.

532
00:30:56.096 --> 00:31:00.056
But of course, what I want you to remember is that these rates at

533
00:31:00.096 --> 00:31:03.936
which you're observing, they have both the mutation rate and the

534
00:31:03.956 --> 00:31:07.596
fixation. So we have to separate those to be able to actually

535
00:31:08.176 --> 00:31:09.976
be talking actually about epistasis.

536
00:31:10.036 --> 00:31:13.516
So generally it occurs when these things are different, but not necessarily.

537
00:31:15.236 --> 00:31:19.056
Okay, so in general, so if you're

538
00:31:19.096 --> 00:31:22.596
considering just two genes, you're going to have four different ways of

539
00:31:23.256 --> 00:31:26.836
going through here. You can either gain A and then

540
00:31:27.096 --> 00:31:31.056
gain B, or B and then A, and that gives you four substitution rates.

541
00:31:31.596 --> 00:31:35.096
And each rate what is going to capture is how fast that step occurs in the

542
00:31:35.116 --> 00:31:37.716
evolutionary process. And as I said, that includes

543
00:31:38.456 --> 00:31:41.335
mutation and the part of selection.

544
00:31:42.856 --> 00:31:46.776
So in our model, the mathematical model, what we're going to do is just estimate

545
00:31:46.786 --> 00:31:50.156
those four rates jointly from tumor sample counts.

546
00:31:50.376 --> 00:31:53.216
And I'll explain very briefly about how we do that.

547
00:31:54.016 --> 00:31:57.196
First, I want you to consider what would happen if you have more genes in a

548
00:31:57.236 --> 00:32:01.036
network. So if you have three genes, you have plenty

549
00:32:01.076 --> 00:32:04.896
more. You have 12 substitution rates and six different evolutionary

550
00:32:04.936 --> 00:32:06.836
pathways where you can go to

551
00:32:07.896 --> 00:32:11.456
having the three mutations, and this gets exponentially more

552
00:32:11.496 --> 00:32:13.356
complicated as you add more genes.

553
00:32:13.436 --> 00:32:13.576
So

554
00:32:14.496 --> 00:32:18.096
already with four genes it's very complicated, all the different pathways

555
00:32:18.136 --> 00:32:22.116
that you can take. And this grows exponentially, and the bad thing about

556
00:32:22.176 --> 00:32:26.036
this is that whenever something grows exponentially, your data doesn't grow

557
00:32:26.076 --> 00:32:29.936
exponentially. So your data generally grows

558
00:32:29.976 --> 00:32:33.695
linearly, so you wait a couple of months, and then you have instead of 500 samples,

559
00:32:33.936 --> 00:32:34.576
600 samples.

560
00:32:35.596 --> 00:32:36.985
But if you have to estimate,

561
00:32:38.216 --> 00:32:41.856
if you just put another two to the n here, then things get out of hand.

562
00:32:41.936 --> 00:32:42.076
So

563
00:32:42.896 --> 00:32:46.776
that's the bad thing about this. But, yeah, we're

564
00:32:46.836 --> 00:32:50.016
going to eventually get more data to be able to get more

565
00:32:50.876 --> 00:32:51.756
genes at the same time.

566
00:32:54.136 --> 00:32:57.616
Just very briefly, I'll tell you a little bit about our model for those

567
00:32:57.736 --> 00:33:00.796
interested in the actual mathematical model part.

568
00:33:02.416 --> 00:33:05.536
What we do is we try to keep a

569
00:33:07.396 --> 00:33:11.116
model that allows us to identify when you have a different somatic

570
00:33:11.296 --> 00:33:13.736
genotype at a specific time.

571
00:33:14.576 --> 00:33:17.936
And what we do is we assume constant substitution rates from

572
00:33:18.396 --> 00:33:18.716
jumps.

573
00:33:19.936 --> 00:33:22.796
So those arrows that I showed you before, we assume that those are going to be

574
00:33:22.836 --> 00:33:26.796
constant all the time. And what that gives us in mathematics is

575
00:33:26.836 --> 00:33:30.296
something called a continuous Markov chain that you can do

576
00:33:31.076 --> 00:33:32.276
mathematical

577
00:33:34.596 --> 00:33:38.576
formulas and can actually get results from

578
00:33:38.596 --> 00:33:42.536
there. So, important thing here is that we're considering only one

579
00:33:42.576 --> 00:33:43.656
gene can mutate at a time.

580
00:33:44.476 --> 00:33:48.176
So note this effects where you have something that completely

581
00:33:48.256 --> 00:33:51.416
changes at a time, but this can be applied for

582
00:33:51.896 --> 00:33:52.336
SMBs.

583
00:33:53.996 --> 00:33:56.856
And in the math part, what we do is we

584
00:33:57.476 --> 00:34:01.456
compute a recursive formula for

585
00:34:01.496 --> 00:34:03.146
this thing, the probabilities.

586
00:34:04.016 --> 00:34:07.736
And then with that formula, then what we can do is just

587
00:34:08.417 --> 00:34:09.816
get input of standard

588
00:34:10.836 --> 00:34:14.516
tumor genomic data, and the output is going to be those substitution rates.

589
00:34:14.696 --> 00:34:18.556
And we still are not done because, as I said, those substitution rates

590
00:34:18.957 --> 00:34:22.156
have the mutation and the selection, and we have to

591
00:34:22.736 --> 00:34:25.596
remove the mutation in order to get the

592
00:34:25.616 --> 00:34:27.156
selection rate.

593
00:34:29.437 --> 00:34:29.676
So

594
00:34:30.776 --> 00:34:34.736
formally what we have is number of tumor samples in each one of the somatic

595
00:34:34.746 --> 00:34:38.316
genotypes, and we consider all the possible somatic genotypes.

596
00:34:39.036 --> 00:34:42.857
And that allows us to build with the formulas that we get from before, that allows

597
00:34:42.917 --> 00:34:46.115
us to build a likelihood, and then it's just a standard

598
00:34:46.516 --> 00:34:50.377
maximize the likelihood kind of approach, or if you want to get more fancy, you

599
00:34:50.437 --> 00:34:53.836
do Bayesian analysis so you can get posteriors out of this.

600
00:34:55.156 --> 00:34:58.636
No special data are required beyond routine tumor sequencing data.

601
00:34:59.076 --> 00:35:02.796
So TCGA, ARC, Project Genie, anything like that, institutional

602
00:35:02.876 --> 00:35:06.536
cohorts, all of those are usable, and you get back the

603
00:35:06.816 --> 00:35:10.716
substitution rates. And then now what you do is you remove from

604
00:35:10.756 --> 00:35:13.816
the substitution rate, this part that is the mutation rate,

605
00:35:14.956 --> 00:35:17.236
which actually I'm calling the mutation rate, but it's

606
00:35:19.256 --> 00:35:21.636
better defined as a neutral fixation rate

607
00:35:22.636 --> 00:35:26.556
for that gene or variant. So it's something that you

608
00:35:26.636 --> 00:35:27.216
get out of

609
00:35:28.076 --> 00:35:28.676
other tools,

610
00:35:29.776 --> 00:35:32.476
something like BNDS that Jaime was talking about.

611
00:35:32.916 --> 00:35:34.876
We have another tool called SigMutCel.

612
00:35:35.496 --> 00:35:39.296
That is a signature base estimation that uses

613
00:35:39.336 --> 00:35:43.296
also covariates. DNDS also uses covariates to get the best

614
00:35:43.336 --> 00:35:47.236
mutation rate possible. And then when you remove this from the

615
00:35:48.636 --> 00:35:52.556
substitution rates, then you're going to obtain finally the selection, and that's

616
00:35:52.596 --> 00:35:56.526
what you're interested in. So if something is larger than one,

617
00:35:56.736 --> 00:36:00.556
then you have a driver there, a

618
00:36:00.596 --> 00:36:03.236
positive acceleration, but you can also compare them between each other.

619
00:36:03.316 --> 00:36:06.876
So if something is twice as much of a driver compared to another

620
00:36:07.296 --> 00:36:07.876
mutation.

621
00:36:09.356 --> 00:36:11.926
You also see whenever you have something that is

622
00:36:11.956 --> 00:36:15.936
counter-selected, and you have a way of saying

623
00:36:16.116 --> 00:36:19.436
if something is actually neutral, so completely passenger.

624
00:36:21.136 --> 00:36:23.416
So as you can see, co-occurrence

625
00:36:23.556 --> 00:36:26.672
wouldoccur

626
00:36:27.892 --> 00:36:31.732
either because this is very large for both of them,

627
00:36:32.092 --> 00:36:35.052
so that wouldn't be an epistatic effect.

628
00:36:35.112 --> 00:36:38.472
So what's important with epistatic effects is

629
00:36:38.872 --> 00:36:40.412
actually the ones that are driven

630
00:36:41.252 --> 00:36:42.452
only by selection.

631
00:36:44.472 --> 00:36:47.532
Okay, so let's go back to this, the actual data that we have.

632
00:36:47.712 --> 00:36:51.332
So now how do we split that in terms

633
00:36:51.412 --> 00:36:55.372
of the model? So the first thing is to obtain those substitution rates.

634
00:36:55.592 --> 00:36:59.392
So what I'm going to be looking at here is each one of the somatic

635
00:36:59.432 --> 00:37:03.232
genotypes. So these very few patients, one or two or

636
00:37:03.272 --> 00:37:07.212
three, maybe, that have the three mutations at the same time, I'm going to

637
00:37:07.252 --> 00:37:10.952
put those into one category. All of these that have APC and

