00:37:10.992 --> 00:37:14.812
KRAS but not BRF, I put those in a

639
00:37:14.852 --> 00:37:18.372
different category, and so on and so forth for each one of the different

640
00:37:19.592 --> 00:37:20.112
subtypes.

641
00:37:21.032 --> 00:37:25.012
So that's how it would look like with TCGA COAD data

642
00:37:25.032 --> 00:37:28.752
that I just showed you. So for some of them, you don't

643
00:37:28.812 --> 00:37:30.352
have any of those three mutations.

644
00:37:31.002 --> 00:37:34.902
And most of the time, what you get is a lot of mutations on the first

645
00:37:35.832 --> 00:37:38.992
categories that have BRF, but not KRAS or APC,

646
00:37:40.212 --> 00:37:40.972
and sometimes,

647
00:37:41.892 --> 00:37:45.852
a little bit more on genes that co-occur together, APC and KRAS, you have

648
00:37:45.952 --> 00:37:46.492
plenty here.

649
00:37:47.712 --> 00:37:51.532
And then as you go to the right of these kind of graphs, then you see

650
00:37:51.632 --> 00:37:52.332
less and less

651
00:37:53.552 --> 00:37:54.912
tumors that have

652
00:37:56.392 --> 00:37:57.332
most of the mutations.

653
00:37:58.312 --> 00:38:01.952
So what you do is you feed that into our mathematical model,

654
00:38:02.252 --> 00:38:04.612
and what's going to give you is those arrows.

655
00:38:04.642 --> 00:38:08.452
So the width of the arrows here is going to be the substitution rate.

656
00:38:09.052 --> 00:38:09.572
And you see

657
00:38:10.712 --> 00:38:13.352
at which rate you're going faster from here to here.

658
00:38:13.692 --> 00:38:15.192
So here you're going very fast,

659
00:38:16.402 --> 00:38:17.312
here not so much.

660
00:38:18.522 --> 00:38:20.392
And that is the substitution rate.

661
00:38:20.622 --> 00:38:24.432
And then what you do is now you remove from those substitution rates the

662
00:38:24.472 --> 00:38:27.512
part that is just purely mutation, that is neutral.

663
00:38:29.132 --> 00:38:32.872
The way that we did this in the first paper was we just fit the

664
00:38:33.232 --> 00:38:36.292
neutral mutation rates that we had from different things.

665
00:38:36.432 --> 00:38:38.572
Actually, the first time we just used the NDS.

666
00:38:39.172 --> 00:38:41.492
So the NDS gives you neutral mutation rates.

667
00:38:42.112 --> 00:38:45.152
So this would be the neutral mutation rates.

668
00:38:45.592 --> 00:38:49.412
What we're doing now, we thought more about it, is

669
00:38:49.792 --> 00:38:53.612
that we actually consider that these neutral mutation rates can

670
00:38:53.672 --> 00:38:56.312
change because you have mutations in other genes.

671
00:38:56.832 --> 00:39:00.552
So not only you have this epistatic effect,

672
00:39:01.132 --> 00:39:04.542
well it's not an epistatic effect, but you have this effect of mutations

673
00:39:04.912 --> 00:39:07.832
influence not only the selection, but they can also

674
00:39:07.912 --> 00:39:11.472
influence the mutation as well. So what we do

675
00:39:11.532 --> 00:39:15.112
now is we consider how many mutations you see in

676
00:39:15.121 --> 00:39:18.752
these different somatic genotypes.

677
00:39:19.292 --> 00:39:22.292
So you consider the average tumor mutation burden.

678
00:39:22.392 --> 00:39:25.512
You see here at the beginning, people are not having as many mutations.

679
00:39:25.972 --> 00:39:29.792
So what we do is we use these average tumor mutation burdens to

