00:39:29.852 --> 00:39:32.292
adjust the jumps of the neutral mutation rates.

681
00:39:32.852 --> 00:39:36.752
So instead of just considering that all the rates never

682
00:39:36.792 --> 00:39:40.752
change, what we see is that whenever you're in these categories

683
00:39:40.792 --> 00:39:41.012
here,

684
00:39:42.652 --> 00:39:44.992
these jumps are going to happen more often

685
00:39:46.192 --> 00:39:49.732
than whenever you were here. So we adjust those neutral mutation rates.

686
00:39:50.332 --> 00:39:53.572
Okay, now and then we take them out of the substitution rates, and this is

687
00:39:54.152 --> 00:39:57.472
actually where you finish, where you have only the selection coefficients.

688
00:39:58.002 --> 00:40:01.792
And then this is where the epistatic effects are actually going to be revealed.

689
00:40:02.952 --> 00:40:06.322
And then you can start asking yourself the questions that you were asking

690
00:40:06.352 --> 00:40:09.942
before. So whenever we were considering, okay, what's

691
00:40:10.232 --> 00:40:13.692
happening that we don't see BRF and KRAS together?

692
00:40:14.172 --> 00:40:17.712
Then you can see that whenever you

